Filing of name approval application with ACRA;
Filing of Company Registration with ACRA;
Maintenance and updating of statutory registers and minutes books based on information given to us by the directors of the Company or as instructed;
Preparation and submission of statutory returns of the Company with Accounting and Corporate Regulatory Authority (ACRA) as required by the Companies Act, Cap. 50;
Preparation of minutes of meetings, resolution of recurring nature and forms required for filing with ACRA;
General advice on matters pertaining to company secretarial matters; and
Filing of duly completed forms and returns with ACRA on your behalf as instructed;
Scanning and filing of all documents into the Shared Google Drive.
Below are some routine matters for which directors’/shareholders’ resolutions, and filing of returns with ACRA are required. We need you to furnish us with timely information to ensure that your secretarial records are duly updated to comply with the requirements of the Companies Act, Cap.50: Late updating will incur a penalty.

Story_Main.numbered_2_para_indent_noupspace:
Appointment, resignation of directors, secretaries, managers, auditors, including changes in their particulars, namely, passport no., address, nationality, etc; (ACRA has to be notified within 30 days of such changes, otherwise penalty applies.)
Changes in situation of registered office address; (ACRA has to be notified within 14 days of such changes)
Allotment of shares; (ACRA has to be notified within 14 days of such changes)
Transfer of shares; 
Changes in particulars of shareholders;
Amendments to the company’s memorandum and articles of association;
Opening and closing of bank accounts;
Acceptance of banking facilities;
Creation and satisfaction of charges;
Purchase and disposal of substantial assets of the company;
Changes in directors’ shareholdings in the company and related corporations (inclusive of foreign incorporated companies);
Holding of annual general meeting which has to be held once every calendar year and not more than 15 months from the date of the last annual general meeting. A newly incorporated company must hold its first annual general meeting within 18 months from the date of its incorporation. Audited or unaudited accounts, as the case may be, must be tabled at the annual general meeting.
